    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/03-pretraining/07-megatron-deepspeed.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: GPUs form a DP x TP x PP (x EP) grid, and each parallelism dimension must be mapped to the network tier it can tolerate: TP all-reduce -> intra-node NVLink (on the critical path, must be fast), PP point-to-point sends -> inter-node InfiniBand (latency-tolerant), DP gradient sync -> outermost, EP all-to-all -> across EP-group boundary.; Sequence parallelism shards activations along the sequence dimension outside the TP GEMM blocks, so only one point in the dataflow holds the full replicated [B,S,H]; all-gather + reduce-scatter replaces a single all-reduce at equal comm volume, cutting steady-state activation memory by a factor of TP.; ZeRO removes redundancy progressively: stage 1 shards optimizer states, stage 2 adds gradients, stage 3 adds parameters -- each stage frees more per-GPU memory but adds communication (stage 3 needs an all-gather per forward pass).; Choosing TP/PP/DP is a constrained funnel: first fit model state (16 bytes/param) onto the smallest GPU set, then set TP = GPUs-per-node (NVLink), then PP across nodes with enough micro-batches to keep the bubble small, then DP = N/(TP*PP), then tune global batch size / gradient accumulation.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  parallelism-degree-decision-funnel, mfu-hfu-flop-accounting, zero-stages, megatron-4d-moe-collectives\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
